# Git Commands and Usage

## Repository Setup

- Initialize a new repo:
  ```bash
  git init
  ```

- Clone an existing repo:
  ```bash
  git clone <repo-url>
  ```

## Basic Workflow

- Check repository status:
  ```bash
  git status
  ```

- Stage files for commit:
  ```bash
  git add <file>
  git add .
  ```

- Commit staged changes:
  ```bash
  git commit -m "Describe your change"
  ```

- View commit history:
  ```bash
  git log --oneline --graph --decorate --all
  ```

## Branching

- List branches:
  ```bash
  git branch
  ```

- Create a branch:
  ```bash
  git branch <branch-name>
  ```

- Switch branches:
  ```bash
  git checkout <branch-name>
  ```

- Create and switch in one step:
  ```bash
  git checkout -b <branch-name>
  ```

- Merge another branch into the current branch:
  ```bash
  git merge <branch-name>
  ```

## Remote Repositories

- Show remotes:
  ```bash
  git remote -v
  ```

- Add a remote:
  ```bash
  git remote add origin <repo-url>
  ```

- Push to remote:
  ```bash
  git push origin <branch-name>
  ```

- Pull changes from remote:
  ```bash
  git pull origin <branch-name>
  ```

- Fetch remote changes without merging:
  ```bash
  git fetch origin
  ```

## GitHub Workflow

1. Create a repository on GitHub.
2. Add the GitHub repo as a remote:
   ```bash
   git remote add origin https://github.com/<username>/<repo>.git
   ```
3. Stage your changes:
   ```bash
   git add .
   ```
4. Commit your work:
   ```bash
   git commit -m "Add description of your changes"
   ```
5. Push to GitHub:
   ```bash
   git push -u origin <branch-name>
   ```

> Use `-u` on the first push to set the upstream branch so future pushes can use `git push`.

## Undo and Fix

- Unstage a file:
  ```bash
  git reset HEAD <file>
  ```

- Discard local changes in a file:
  ```bash
  git checkout -- <file>
  ```

- Revert a commit by creating a new commit:
  ```bash
  git revert <commit-hash>
  ```

- Reset to a previous commit (use with care):
  ```bash
  git reset --hard <commit-hash>
  ```

## Helpful Commands

- Show differences for unstaged changes:
  ```bash
  git diff
  ```

- Show differences for staged changes:
  ```bash
  git diff --staged
  ```

- Stash changes temporarily:
  ```bash
  git stash
  git stash pop
  ```

- See the last commit details:
  ```bash
  git show
  ```

## Tips

- Use descriptive commit messages.
- Keep branches small and focused.
- Pull frequently to stay up to date with shared work.
- Use `git status` often to avoid surprises.
